First stop for afternoon snack and in place of lunch. I finally stop by here for some of their bread and oh man was it delicious to smell the pastries while waiting in line. Was the line worth it? I thought so. Will I be back cause I won't be able to follow their cookbook as well? Definite yes.

This is one of those places in SF that get a LOT of hype, and though it isn't bad, I just don't really get why it receives the level of praise that it does. Service is subpar - Employees are generally terse and not particularly friendly. You can really tell that they're sick of always dealing with a line of customers out the door. The pastries - Inconsistent. The last croissant I had here was actually slightly burnt, which made it very crispy and flaky on top but in a bad way. I've had some sort of berry crumble pastry here too, but it was just forgettable. Honestly I much prefer b.Patisserie over Tartine. Better quality pastries, and shorter lines. If you need further convincing, for all my foodies out there: The bakers at b.Patisserie recently won a James Beard award for Outstanding Baker, and despite all the attention it gets, Tartine wasn't even nominated.

Tartine Bakery is going to be the ruin of any diet plans! Whenever I do want to splurge in the city, I make a stop by Tartine. As one gets closer to the establishment, one can delightfully enjoy the smells of the bakery. Unfortunately, everytime I drop by there is always a line to order something from their delicious bakery with the morning times understandably having the longest lines. I have ordered a variety of different things here but here are a list of things that I have particularly enjoyed: Banana creme tart: The tart particularly nails the banana flavor with nicely sliced pieces of banana layered in the filling. But the nice surprise is the layers of milk chocolate along the pie crust which make for a beautiful match made in tastebud heaven. Morning buns: They would be a welcome pick me up for any day! Not knowing what these were, they are basically a flaky croissant like pastry lightly flavored with a orange zest that could easily be laced with crack! Croque monsieur: Enveloped with golden bread to indicate the buttery goodness that has soaked in each of the slices and then filled with hearty pieces of cheese and ham. Surprisingly, it never feels awfully heavy where I am in an induced food coma. These come with pickled carrots that definitely provide a welcome acidity to cut through. The service is fast and friendly. The space inside the actual establishment is small so if you are planning to have a nice brunch with a bunch of your friends you are better off planning to take these goodies to go and walk off to the park. Parking is limited and again may be better to walk over. Overall, Tartine Bakery has a lot of great pastries that are worth picking up and enjoying in the city.

Been coming to Tartine for years. I expect a line every time, but am always amazed at how slow the cashiers are. It doesn't seem to be a problem with kitchen efficiency. Maybe waiting in line is part of the planned experience, but it seems unnecessary. I've been told I can skip the line if I'm just getting coffee. But there's never a free cashier -- one that isn't already servicing someone that's been waiting in a long line. I wish Tartine would work on this.

Unfortunately the pastries didn't amaze me. We got the lemon cake, the coconut macaroon and the almond croissant. Nothing stands out. On the bright side, the line moved very fast.

My top picks: morning bun, banana cream tart, tres leches cake, any of their breads Tartine holds a special place in my heart. As much as I hate waiting in lines, I would gladly do it again and again for Tartine (plus the lines usually aren't horrible - probably about 30 min on average). It's a small cafe with limited seating and it's usually cramped with people eating and waiting for their orders. I've yet to have anything savory here but that is on my list. I know people rave about their croque monsieur and the lemon tart. Choose any of my top picks for sweet and I'd say you're good to go :) The Tartine Manufactory has these items also if you're looking for a larger space.

We got the pan au chocolat, a croissant, a lemon tart, and quiche with ham and potato. OH MY DEAR SWEET LORD IN HEAVEN. Everything was out-of-this-world incredible. I'm not exaggerating.     10/17/2016Previous review

    As I turn the corner of Guerrero I see a line of 20 people standing out in the cold five minutes before this place opens. Rain, sleet or snow couldn't move these people out of that line this Sunday 10/16/16 7:55 am.

    Local regulars as well as people from all over the world are in this line and they know of this place through all sorts of different social media. I chat it up in the line to pass some time.

    Yes, this is my favorite bakery in the city too. I can understand all this who - ha. It feels like your in line at some uber-cool club -- only don't mistake it. Those bar/club lines are likely artificially created to create buzz... this line is for real. We are all people who are tired of mediocre baked goods and there just isn't enough for everybody - especially those who are not diligent in waking up early.

    I've been to this location at noon. A lot of the breads they are known for are sold out and good luck getting one of their unique dark almond croissants at that hour.

    Ready for some bad food terminology? Buckle up!! I got one of their hot breakfast sandwiches. You know that ones that are open faced and have cheese and ham and pepper corn and tomatoes. Oh its so good but I'm sure thats not the official name. Its hot if and crunchy and just perfect. A couple different tomatoes on top and two different types of ham - one smoked. On the side it will come with a pickled carrot that you eat after your done where you can indulge in while you think fondly about the sandwich that is now gone.

    What else to order? The berry dealie with sliced almonds and a crunchy firm bottom is a must. Its crumbly and has marzipan in the middle and since it has some heft it will be satisfying. Nope this is no lightweight here.

    The brownie with perfectly toasted hazelnuts in a cookie crust is also a must. From experience I can tell you that at noon if there is one left it is just a miracle.

    Their dark almond croissants are crazy good too. If you are a Tartine noobie you might think that they are a tad overcooked but that is just the way they are meant to be for extra flavor.

    Morning buns are also mind blowing. Aha!! Here I remembered the official name. They are so good yet so simple. At the bottom of the pan there is some sugar that caramelizes for a pleasant surprise as you bite in.

    I go here and I point away at all of the desserts. I have to have one of everything. Its so good here you can't choose. I had just gone to Schuberts the day before for a almond croissant that was like one you would find at Starbucks and and a berry tart with a soggy bottom and it really made me appreciate this place all over again. I have never gotten anything that was less than perfectly prepared.

    What will it cost you? If you go with a date and have a couple coffees and two breakfast sandwiches and then two desserts to go it could easily cost $50 or so. But its so worth it. Based on simple supply and demand economic rules they should raise their prices... but thank goodness they finally opened the Manufactory that should ease up the riots in the morning in front of this location.

    Perfectly beautiful store fronts are overrated like all the girls out there with heavy makeup. Its what is on the inside that matters.

    Tartine doesn't put much effort into their store front. Maybe its because they are so confident in their pastries they don't need to lure people in with neon signs or deceptive 45 minute make up routines.

    Crafting all these sugary goods is their focus and it takes up all their time. The slightly shabby store front makes all the hipster regulars feel at home because that is the way they want their choice coffee shop to look. And these are the ones to cater to - they are happy to pay $10 for a cup of coffee and a brownie. If it makes them happy to walk past missing pink tiles one the way in so be it.

    As you walk in there is not much signage (if any at all?). Just look for the long lines out the door. Its like one of those cool speakeasy bars in the city that you may go to. Inside minimal art decoration and fast modern music of a slightly louder than average volume that makes everything seem urgent. Wow, I've got somewhere to go. Gotta eat and run.

    This stuff gets sold out quick, so wake up early. I feel so blessed to have gotten the opportunity to pay $6.50 for the last brownie with all the beautifully roasted hazel nuts on top. Perfectly crunchy cookie crust (must have been the result of a blind bake?) and topped with a bit of powder sugar.

    In the end it makes me happy to walk past those missing pink tiles on the way in and to have the best desserts imaginable. It satisfies the hipster in me. I wouldn't want it any other way. Their cool confidence is just as sexy as a lady out there so comfortable with herself she doesn't have to hide behind caked on makeup.

    One of my favorite dessert spots just like Ghirardelli for the hot fudge sundae and Crispian bakery for the almonnd croissant.

    My top picks: morning bun, banana cream tart, tres leches cake, any of their breads

    Tartine holds a special place in my heart. As much as I hate waiting in lines, I would gladly do it again and again for Tartine (plus the lines usually aren't horrible - probably about 30 min on average). It's a small cafe with limited seating and it's usually cramped with people eating and waiting for their orders.

    I've yet to have anything savory here but that is on my list. I know people rave about their croque monsieur and the lemon tart. Choose any of my top picks for sweet and I'd say you're good to go :)

    Soooo this is the best bakery I've ever been to in my life. We heard about this place a few months ago and believe me, it was very hyped up. We got there at about 9:30 and there was a line out the door. However, the line moved quickly, which was great because we were starving. Oh and I should mention that it smells amazing outside as you are waiting in line...like a buttery, sugary, happiness sort of scent. We got the pan au chocolat, a croissant, a lemon tart, and quiche with ham and potato. OH MY DEAR SWEET LORD IN HEAVEN. Everything was out-of-this-world incredible. I'm not exaggerating. I'm actually underselling it. My husband and I didn't speak the entire time we ate. We devoured everything. If it was socially appropriate for me to lick the crumbs off the table, I would have. This place exceeded my expectations. I am so mad we didn't order more, even though this is way more breakfast than we are used to eating.This is one of those places that the food speaks for itself. Even if the service sucked (which it didn't) or the place was crowded and messy (which it kind of was), I don't give a damn because I just ate the most delicious pastries I've ever tasted. I'm thinking about booking another trip to SF this month just for this bakery. I miss it so much already!!
